 Novartis Salespeople Covered by Wage Laws, Court Says  
 Novartis AG’s  sales representatives are covered by federal
wage-and-hour laws requiring payment of overtime, a three-judge
panel of the U.S.  appeals court  in New York ruled yesterday.  
 The panel overturned a lower-court finding that the sales
representatives fell under exceptions to the federal Fair Labor
Standards Act for outside sales people and administrative
workers.  
 The decision affects about 2,500 current and former sales
representatives employed by Novartis between March 23, 2000 and
April 7, 2007, who are suing for unpaid overtime, according to
the court’s decision.  
 Eric Althoff, a Novartis spokesman, didn’t immediately
return a voice-mail message seeking comment.  
 The case is Re Novartis Wage and Hour Litigation, 09-437,
2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, (Manhattan).  
 Ex-IKB CEO Should Be Convicted of Manipulation, Prosecutor Says  
 German prosecutors said the former  IKB Deutsche
Industriebank AG  chief executive officer, Stefan Ortseifen,
should be convicted of market manipulation and receive a 10-
month suspended sentence.  
 Ortseifen deliberately tried, in a press release, to hide
the effect and mislead investors regarding the effect of the
U.S. subprime crisis on the lender in a press release issued in
July 2007, prosecutor Nils Bussee said in closing arguments
today. IKB was bailed out in 2007 by KfW Group and banking
associations.  
 Ortseifen’s lawyer Reinhard von Dalwigk declined to comment
today, saying the defense will rebut in closing arguments next
week. Ortseifen has denied the charges during trial.  
 Trafigura Ruling Must Be Reviewed, Dutch Supreme Court Says  
 A Dutch court must re-examine whether Trafigura Beheer BV
Chief Executive Officer Claude Dauphin should be prosecuted over
the export of waste to Ivory Coast in 2006.  
 The Dutch Supreme Court said the Amsterdam Appeals Court
has to review its 2008 ruling, which barred the prosecution of
Dauphin, citing insufficient  evidence . The lower tribunal used a
“limited interpretation” of European Union rules against
exporting waste to countries including Ivory Coast, the court in
The Hague said in a ruling on its  website  yesterday.  
 Residents of Abidjan claimed the dumped waste caused deaths
and illness. Trafigura, which denied responsibility for the
dumping, paid the Ivory Coast government $198.4 million in 2007
for the removal of the waste and last year settled a lawsuit
filed by residents who claimed to have fallen ill.  
 Trafigura is on trial before an Amsterdam court for
allegedly concealing the waste’s composition. The court is
scheduled to rule on July 23.  
 Irving Stitsky Gets 85-Year Sentence in $23 Million Fraud  
 Irving Stitsky, who defrauded more than 250 people in a $23
million fraudulent real estate investment, was sentenced to 85
years in prison in Manhattan federal court. U.S. District Judge
Kimba Wood sentenced Stitsky, whom she called “an inveterate
con man,” to the maximum for his third securities fraud
conviction.  
