 Iceland Lenders May Lose $4.3 Billion on Supreme Court Ruling  
 Iceland’s lenders stand to lose as much as $4.3 billion,
after a court ruling last month found that some foreign loans
were illegal, according to Finance Minister Steingrimur J.
Sigfusson.  
 Such loans are the “largest single loan category of the
banks,” Sigfusson told a radio station in  Bylgjan  yesterday. If
capital on all the loans in the category is written down by 40
percent to 60 percent, “we’re talking about enormous amounts.”  
 The Supreme Court ruled June 16 that loans indexed to
foreign-currency rates were illegal in three cases involving
private car loans and a corporate property loan. The decisions
may mean that borrowers with such loans are only obliged to
repay the principal in kronur, making the lenders liable for
currency losses on about $28 billion in debt.  
 Magnus Thoroddsen, a former president of Iceland’s Supreme
Court, said contractual rates apply unless the banks sue and
win. The FSA will provide parliament’s Trade Committee with a
breakdown of the cost of the ruling to lenders on July 9.  
